@digama: this doesn't seem to be working properly for Std, but I can't see what LeanTar is doing with my `base` argument.

Can you teach it a verbose mode that prints out where the extracted files are being written to?

The `else config` looks suspicious, that means to skip the file entirely.

The way this works is that you pass a json argument containing either `pathStr` or `{"file": pathStr, "base": base}`, and `base`, if provided, overrides the `baseDir` which is passed as the `-C` argument (with default value `.`). This says to decompress `pathStr` which is an ltar file, with `base` as the base for all generated files. The ltar file contains a list of relative paths and these are joined to `base`.

For the usual ltars generated by CI, the paths will be of the form:
* `.lake/build/lib/Mathlib/Tactic.trace` (and `.lake/build/lib/Mathlib/Tactic.{olean,ilean,c}[.hash]`) for files in mathlib
* `.lake/build/lib/proofwidgets/.lake/build/lib/ProofWidgets/Compat.trace` (etc) for files not in mathlib

If you would like to trim these paths to something shorter, you can do so by setting the `-C` argument appropriately during the packing stage. (But don't forget to do something to change the root hash such as adding whitespace in `lake-manifest.json`, because these ltars will not be compatible with previous builds.)

Thanks!

`lake/build/lib/proofwidgets/.lake/build/lib/ProofWidgets/Compat.trace` looks like a bad path to me. Did you mean `lake/packages/proofwidgets/.lake/build/lib/ProofWidgets/Compat.trace`?

yes. `.lake/packages/proofwidgets/.lake/build/lib/ProofWidgets/Compat.trace` more specifically. (A cheap way to find out without additional tooling is `strings NNN.ltar | grep proofwidgets`, where `NNN.ltar` is the output of `lake exe cache lookup ProofWidgets/Compat.lean`)
This seems a bit unnecessary, why not just pass the `packageDir` in instead if you need it afterward?
I think this is now moot, the data is now carried around in a reader monad instead.
